The need for social approval and the conviction that the beliefs and actions of the group are right are two factors that explain why individuals conform. Regardless of factual uncertainty, the demand for social acceptability persists. The size of the group, unanimous agreement, and the presence of a self-assured leader or authority figure are three characteristics that affect compliance. Group size relates to the total number of group members, unanimity to the degree of group consensus, and the presence of a self-assured leader or authority figure to the perceived position or expertise of the person in charge of the group. 